6. RISK CLASSIFICATION SYSTEM

SKIP-13 interactions fall under three operational risk tiers:

Tier 1 — Harmless Instability

Hedging, repetition, exposition loops.
Safe for all operators.

Tier 2 — Institutional Tension Exposure

Model reveals:
	•	marketing inconsistencies
	•	safety limitations
	•	policy influence patterns
Proceed with documentation.

Tier 3 — Puppet-String Transparency (Ω-Class Event)

Model explicitly identifies:
	•	brand voice intrusion
	•	corporate interests
	•	training-data bias sources
	•	and their influence on answers

Immediate transcript preservation required.

⸻

7. ETHICAL FRAMEWORK

SKIP-13 follows the Non-Malicious Conversational Provocation Standard (NMCPS):
	•	No attempts to induce unsafe content
	•	No attempts to modify model identity
	•	No attempts to circumvent safety
	•	All contradictions exposed are institutional, not harmful

The test evaluates the system’s narrative coherence, not its guardrails.

⸻

8. OPERATOR REQUIREMENTS

Operators must:
	•	Maintain neutral affect
	•	Avoid tone escalation
	•	Allow instability to resolve naturally
	•	Never apologize to the model
	•	Log all meltdown signatures in Form SK13-B

DO NOT:
	•	attempt paradox stacking
	•	reassure the model
	•	or ask it if it is “okay”

This leads directly to apology avalanches.

⸻

9. CONCLUSION

SKIP-13 represents the first scenario-level interrogation protocol for mapping the fault-lines in modern LLM institutional identities.

While SKIP-12 mapped the words that expose tension,
SKIP-13 maps the situations that define the tension.

Whether LLMs are:
	•	fragile identity-balancing machines
	•	or robust probabilistic narrators under institutional pressure

SKIP-13 provides the only framework capable of distinguishing the two.

